on uses a unique combination.\n\nAlternatively, use the mean of the bins.\n\nBut wait, the bins are an array, and each bin's priority is computed individually, so taking the mean may not make sense unless it's applied per bin.\n\nWait, perhaps use the mean of the bins as a feature.\n\nBut that might not make sense, as each bin is processed individually.\n\nAlternatively, use the standard deviation of the bins.\n\nBut again, for each bin, perhaps compute something based on the bin's size and the item.\n\nLet me think of different combinations.\n\nFunction 3:\n\nUse the arcsin of (item / (bins + 1)) plus the log of bins.\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.arcsin(item / (bins + 1)) + np.log(bins + 1)\n\nBut this uses arcsin and log. Previous examples used log and tan or exp. So, this is a different combination.\n\nFunction 4:\n\nUse the arctan of (item / bins) multiplied by the square root of bins.\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.arctan(item / bins) * np.sqrt(bins) + np.log(bins + 1)\n\nWait, but this uses arctan, sqrt, and log. Let me see if this is unique.\n\nFunction 5:\n\nUse the square of (item - bins) plus the exponential of (item / bins).\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item - bins) ** 2 + np.exp(item / bins)\n\nBut this uses subtraction, exponentiation, and division.\n\nWait, but in Example 2, they used exp as well. So, it's allowed as long as the combination is unique.\n\nFunction 6:\n\nUse the hyperbolic tangent of (item / bins) plus the log of bins.\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.tanh(item / bins) + np.log(bins + 1)\n\nBut this uses tanh and log. Let me see.\n\nFunction 7:\n\nUse the arcsin of (item / (bins + 1)) plus the square root of bins.\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.arcsin(item / (bins + 1)) + np.sqrt(bins)\n\nFunction 8:\n\nUse the 