that each function is unique in its combination of operations and functions.\n\nI think these 10 functions should satisfy the requirement of being unique combinations.\n\nNow, I can write each function as a separate Python function, ensuring that the code is correct and returns a numpy array of the same shape as bins.\n\nEach function will take the item and bins as inputs and return the computed priority array.\n\nI need to make sure that the functions are valid and do not have any syntax errors.\n\nI can now write each function one by one, ensuring that each uses a different combination of allowed operations.\n</think>\n\nHere are 10 unique implementations of the `priority` function for the bin packing problem:\n\n```python\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item + np.pi) * np.exp(bins) + np.sin(bins)\n```\n\n```python\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.log(item + bins) * np.exp(item) + np.cos(bins)\n```\n\n```python\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.log(bins + 1)) * np.exp(item) + np.sin(item)\n```\n\n```python\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item / (bins + np.e)) * np.exp(item) + np.cos(bins)\n```\n\n```python\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.sin(bins)) + np.exp(item - bins)\n```\n\n```python\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.log(item + bins) * np.exp(bins) + np.tan(item)\n```\n\n```python\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * (bins ** 0.5)) + np.log(bins + item)\n```\n\n```python\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.exp(bins)) + np.sin(item) * np.cos(bins)\n```\n\n```python\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item + np.pi) * np.log(bins + 1) + np.exp(item)\n```\n\n```python\ndef priori