to avoid repeating the same structure as previous examples. Each function should have a unique combination of operations and logic.\n\n### Additional Examples:\n\nExample 1:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item + np.sum(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\nExample 2:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.mean(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.log10(bins) * np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\nThese examples use a combination of arithmetic operations, exponential functions, and trigonometric functions to compute the priority.\n\n### Task:\nGenerate 10 UNIQUE correct implementations of the `priority` function, each using a unique combination of the allowed operations.\n\n### Instructions for the assistant:\nYou are to generate 10 unique implementations of the `priority` function, each using a unique combination of allowed operations. Each implementation must be a valid Python function with the correct signature, and it must return an array of the same size as bins. The functions should be as unique as possible, using different mathematical operations and combinations.\n\nMake sure that each function is vectorized and handles all possible inputs correctly, including when bins are empty or item is 0 or 1.\n\nThe functions should be as different as possible from each other to ensure uniqueness.\n</think>\n\n### Implementation 1:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - bins) * np.log10(1 + bins) + np.sin(np.pi * item / bins)\n\n### Implementation 2:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.log2(1 + bins) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.cos(np.pi * item / bins)\n\n### Implementation 3:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item + np.mean(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.log10(bins) * np.sin(np.pi * item / bins)\n\n### Implementation 4:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - bins) * np.log2(1 + bins) + np.tan(np.pi * item / bins)\n\n### Implementation 5:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.mean(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.log10(bins) * np.cos(np.pi * item / bins)\n\n### Implementation 6:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - bins) * np.log10(1 + bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item + bins))\n\n### Implementation 7:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item + np.sum(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.log2(bins) * np.cos(np.pi * item / bins)\n\n### Implementation 8:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.log2(1 + bins) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.tan(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\n### Implementation 9:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.max(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.log10(bins) * np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * (np.mean(bins) + np.std(bins))) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.log(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) * np.cos(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.tan(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.log1p(bins)\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.log2(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.mean(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.tan(np.pi * (item / bins)) * np.log(bins)\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    [compute and return the priority array]\n\n### Deliverables:\n10 such functions, each with a unique combination of operations.\n\n### Note:\nEach function should be self-contained and not rely on any external variables or functions beyond the allowed operations and numpy.\n\n### Note:\nThe functions are for demonstration purposes and do not need to be the most optimal heuristics.\n</think>\n\n### Solution Code\n\n```python\nimport numpy as np\nimport math\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.log2(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n```\n\n```python\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.mean(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.tan(np.pi * (item / bins)) * np.log(bins)\n```\n\n```python\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.sum(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.cos(np.pi * (item / bins)) * np.log2(bins)\n```\n\n```python\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.max(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.arctan(np.pi * (item / bins)) * np.log10(bins)\n```\n\n```python\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.min(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) * np.log(bins)\n```\n\n```python\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.mean(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.cos(np.pi * (item / bins)) * np.log2(bins)\n```\n\n```python\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.max(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.tan(np.pi * (item / bins)) * np.log10(bins)\n```\n\n```python\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.min(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.arctan(np.pi * (item / bins)) * np.log(bins)\n```\n\n```python\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.mean(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) * np.log2(bins)\n```\n\n```python\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.max(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.cos(np.pi * (item / bins)) * np.log10(bins)\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.logaddexp(item, bins) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * bins / item)\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.min(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.tan(np.pi * (item / bins))\n', "def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    # This is a simple example where bins can fit the item get a priority of 1, others get 0.\n    # This is not a good heuristic but serves as an example.\n    can_fit = (bins >= item).astype(float)\n    return can_fit\n\n### Note:\n\nThe example above is just for illustration. You need to create more sophisticated functions.\n\n### How to Proceed:\n\n1. **Understand the Allowed Operations**: Review the list of allowed mathematical functions and array operations.\n\n2. **Create Different Combinations**: For each of the 10 functions, combine the allowed operations in a unique way to compute the priority.\n\n3. **Ensure Correct Shape**: Make sure that each function returns an array of the same shape as the bins array.\n\n4. **Test Each Function**: Although you won't run them, ensure that each function logically makes sense and uses the allowed operations correctly.\n\n### Final Deliverable:\n\nSubmit 10 different priority functions, each using a unique combination of allowed operations, following the exact function signature.\n\n### Note:\n\n- The priority function is part of a larger bin-packing algorithm. The algorithm will select the bin with the highest priority score for the item.\n\n- The priority function must be efficient and vectorized, as it will be used in a loop for many items and bins.\n\n- Avoid using loops in the function; rely on vectorized operations for efficiency.\n\n### Example of a More Sophisticated Function:\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    # Compute the available space in each bin\n    available = bins\n    # Compute the ratio of available space to item size\n    ratio = available / item\n    # Compute the priority as the ratio multiplied by some function of the bin size\n    priority = ratio * np.log(1 + ratio)\n    return priority\n\n### Another Example:\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    # Use a combination of exponential and sine functions\n    return np.exp(item) * np.sin(np.pi * bins / item)\n\n### Note:\n\nThe above examples are just for illustration. You need to create more diverse functions.\n\n### Conclusion:\n\nEach of the 10 functions should be unique in the combination of operations they use. They should not just be slight variations of each other but should represent different approaches to computing the priority.\n\n### Deliverable:\n\nYou must provide 10 unique implementations of the priority function, each using a different combination of the allowed operations.\n\n### Final Note:\n\nMake sure that each function is self-contained, uses only the allowed operations, and returns an array of the same shape as the bins array.\n</think>\n\n### Implementation 1:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.logaddexp(item, bins) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * bins / item)\n\n### Implementation 2:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.min(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.tan(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\n### Implementation 3:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.log1p(item) * np.log1p(bins) + np.tanh(np.pi * item / bins)\n\n### Implementation 4:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item) * np.cos(np.pi * bins / item) + np.log(bins + item)\n\n### Implementation 5:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.log2(item + bins) * np.sinh(np.pi * item / bins)\n\n### Implementation 6:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item) * np.log(bins) + np.tanh(np.pi * (item / bins)) * np.log10(item + bins)\n\n### Implementation 7:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.log(item + bins) * np.cos(np.pi * item / bins) + np.sinh(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\n### Implementation 8:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.log1p(item) * np.log1p(bins) + np.exp(np.pi * (item / bins))\n\n### Implementation 9:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.log2(item) * np.log2(bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) * np.cos(np.pi * (item / bins))\n", 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.max(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.tan(np.pi * (item / bins))\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.log10(np.max(bins))) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.tan(np.pi * (item / bins)) + item * np.max(bins)\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.log10(item) * np.exp(bins)\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.tan(np.pi * (item / bins)) * np.max(bins)\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (np.max(bins) - bins) * item\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.sin(np.log10(bins) + item)\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return item ** (bins / np.mean(bins))\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item / bins) * np.exp(-bins)\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item - bins) * (item + bins)\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.nda